# verify.yaml — language-agnostic example for `maestro verify write`.
#
# This file lists verification commands the daemon may run after a Worker
# reports a task as completed. The example below uses git-only commands so it
# works for any repository regardless of language (Go, Python, JavaScript,
# Rust, research notes, documentation, ...). Replace the entries with the
# verification suite that fits your project — or leave them as-is and the
# daemon will gate worker output through `git diff --check` only.
#
# Usage:
#   maestro verify write --command-id <command_id> --config-file verify.yaml
# or via stdin:
#   cat verify.yaml | maestro verify write --command-id <command_id> --config-file -
#
# Constraints (enforced by VerifyConfig.Validate):
#   - Each command must fit on a single YAML scalar (no embedded newline /
#     carriage return).
#   - Each command runs under `bash -c`, so shell metacharacters (`;`,
#     `&&`, `||`, pipelines, redirects, env substitutions) are allowed —
#     write the command exactly as you would on a shell prompt.
#   - Categories must be one of: build, lint, test, typecheck, security,
#     performance. Any other top-level key under `verify:` is rejected
#     with a helpful error rather than being silently dropped.
#
# Notes for autonomous LLM orchestration:
#   - Verify is best-effort. A failing verify command schedules a repair
#     task; if the repair succeeds, the plan is treated as completed
#     (lineage-aware DeriveStatus, see internal/plan/lineage.go).
#   - Avoid commands that depend on a hot dev cache (e.g., `pnpm turbo run
#     build` without a prior install) — they produce environment-driven
#     false negatives. If you need them, also run the install step.
#   - Categories below are advisory groupings; all listed commands run.

verify:
  build:
    - git diff --check
  lint: []
  test: []
  typecheck: []
  # security and performance categories are optional (C-3 extension):
  # security: []
  # performance: []
